# Internationalization — i18n

All user-facing text externalized via react-i18next.

## Structure

- `src/translations/` — all JSON translation files (content). Translators work here.
- `src/i18n/` — config and types only. No content.

```
translations/
├── en/
│   ├── common.json, hero.json, services.json, about.json, contact.json, validation.json
├── el/  (mirrors en/ exactly)
└── index.ts
```

## Namespaces

```ts
export enum TranslationNamespace {
  COMMON = "common", HERO = "hero", SERVICES = "services",
  ABOUT = "about", CONTACT = "contact", BOOKING_FORM = "bookingForm", VALIDATION = "validation",
}
```

## Usage

```tsx
const { t } = useTranslation(TranslationNamespace.SERVICES);
return <h2>{t("heading")}</h2>;
```

## Translation Keys

- Dot-separated, namespaced, descriptive: `services.oilChange.title`
- NOT location-based: avoid `section2.card1.heading`
- Include keys for ALL translatable attributes: text, `aria-label`, `placeholder`, `alt`

## New Component — Translation Checklist

1. Create `translations/en/myComponent.json` and `translations/el/myComponent.json`
2. Add namespace to `TranslationNamespace` enum
3. Use `useTranslation` from day one
4. Populate both locales. Use `[TODO: translate]` for untranslated Greek

**No component is complete until translation files exist in all locales.**

## Rules

- Zero hardcoded user-facing strings — headings, labels, buttons, placeholders, errors, alt text, aria-label
- Locale folders mirror each other exactly with identical keys
- Date/number/currency formatting via `Intl` APIs or i18next
- Default: English (en). Additional: Greek (el)
- Lazy-load namespaces per route/section
